gomodel:SYNGO_5267  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 4: Acute loss of palmitoyl-LIMK1 impairs Fluorescence Recovery After Photobleaching (FRAP) of GFP-actin in dendritic spines.\n\n\"Taken together, these data suggest that the predominant effect of loss of palmitoyl-LIMK1 on GFP-actin turnover is to reduce the pool of mobile actin in spines. This deficit is initially surprising, because LIMK1 is best known as a negative regulator of cofilin, and increased cofilin activity in the absence of palmitoyl-LIMK1 might be expected to increase actin turnover. We consider possible molecular explanations for this finding in the 'Discussion', but taken together, these results suggest that palmitoyl-LIMK1 is essential for normal actin turnover in spines.\"\n\nFigure 5: Palmitoyl-LIMK1 is required for spine-specific activity-dependent morphological plasticity.\n\nFigure 6: Prolonged loss of palmitoyl-LIMK1 reduces dendritic spine and synapse number.. Experimental description: the cultured neurons were from rat; \"Hippocampi were dissected from E18 rat embryos and neurons were cultured in Neurobasal/B27 as described\". Doesn't matter much, protein alignment via uniprot online tool showed protein from both species are the same length and have a 95.21% sequence identity." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" ;
        dc:date           "2023-03-09" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_5267" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

